11 “SECTION 1. ORS 442.615 is amended to read:
12 “442.615. (1) As used in this section:
13 “(a) ‘Financial assistance’ includes:
14 “(A) Charity care, as defined in ORS 442.601; or
15 “(B) An adjustment to a patient’s costs for care under ORS 442.614 (1)(a).
16 “(b) ‘Hospital’ has the meaning given that term in ORS 442.612.
17 “(2) Using the process prescribed by the Oregon Health Authority under subsection (3) of this
18 section, a hospital licensed under ORS 441.025 shall screen a patient for presumptive eligibility for
19 financial assistance if the patient:
20 “(a) Is uninsured;
21 “(b) Is enrolled in the state medical assistance program; or
22 “(c) Owes the hospital more than [$500] $1,500 for a single hospital encounter.
23 “(3) The authority shall adopt by rule the process for screening a patient for presumptive eligi-
24 bility for financial assistance under subsection (2) of this section. The rules and process must:
25 “(a) Prohibit a hospital from requiring a patient to provide documentation or other verification;
26 “(b) Ensure that the process will not cause any negative impact on the patient’s credit score;
27 “(c) Require a hospital, before sending a bill to the patient, to conduct the screening and apply
28 any financial assistance for which the patient qualifies to the bill; and
29 “(d) Require the hospital to notify a patient if the patient has been screened and to explain to
30 the patient, in language approved by the authority, how to apply for financial assistance if financial
31 assistance was denied, or how to apply for additional financial assistance above what the patient
32 received.
33 “(4) A patient may apply for financial assistance:
34 “(a) If the patient was screened for presumptive eligibility for financial assistance and was found
35 not to be eligible or the patient disagrees with the amount of the financial assistance that was of-
LC 241/HB 4040-36

1 fered;
2 “(b) If a patient was not screened for presumptive eligibility for financial assistance; or
3 “(c) Any time up to 12 months after a patient pays for the services that the hospital provided.
4 “(5) A hospital may require a patient who applies for financial assistance under subsection (4)
5 of this section to provide documentation or verification of information reported as necessary for the
6 hospital to determine the patient’s eligibility for financial assistance.
7 “(6) If a patient applies for financial assistance after having paid for the services and the patient
8 is found to have been eligible for financial assistance when the services were provided:
9 “(a) The hospital shall refund the amount of financial assistance for which the patient qualified;
10 “(b) If the hospital previously determined, incorrectly, that the patient did not qualify for fi-
11 nancial assistance for the services based on information provided by the patient at the time of the
12 incorrect determination, the hospital shall also pay the patient interest on the amount of financial
13 assistance at the rate set by the Federal Reserve and any other associated reasonable costs, such
14 as legal expenses and fees, incurred by the patient in securing financial assistance; and
15 “(c) If the hospital sold the debt to a collection agency or authorized a collection agency to
16 collect debts on behalf of the hospital, the hospital shall notify the collection agency that the debt
17 is invalid.
18 “(7) If a patient applies for financial assistance and the hospital determines that the patient is
19 eligible for financial assistance based on documentation provided by the patient, the patient’s eligi-
20 bility for financial assistance continues for nine months following the hospital’s determination, and
21 the patient may not be required to reapply for financial assistance for services provided during that
22 nine-month period.
23 “(8)(a) A hospital must have a written process that is in plain English, and in other languages
24 as required by law, for a patient to appeal a hospital’s denial of financial assistance, in whole or in
25 part, and that allows the patient, or an individual acting on behalf of the patient, to correct any
26 deficiencies in documentation or to request a review of the denial by the hospital’s chief financial
27 officer or the chief financial officer’s designee. The authority shall prescribe by rule the require-
28 ments for the appeal process.
29 “(b) If a hospital denies a patient’s application for financial assistance, whether in whole or in
30 part, the hospital must notify the patient of the denial and include in the notice an explanation of
31 the hospital’s appeal process.
32 “(9) During the pendency of an appeal that is filed using a hospital’s appeal process under sub-
33 section (8) of this section, if:
34 “(a) The hospital has initiated collection activities, the hospital must suspend all collection ac-
35 tivities; and
36 “(b) The hospital sold the debt under appeal to a collection agency or has authorized a col-
37 lection agency to collect debts on behalf of the hospital, the hospital must notify the collection
38 agency to suspend collection activities.
