38 “SECTION 11. ORS 427.191 is amended to read:
39 “427.191. (1) As used in this section:
40 “(a) ‘Agency’ means an agency that hires, trains and supervises direct support professionals us-
41 ing state funds received from the Department of Human Services.
42 “(b) ‘Attendant care services’ means services provided directly to an individual with a disability
43 to assist with activities of daily living, instrumental activities of daily living and health-related
44 tasks.
45 “(c) ‘Child’ means an individual under 18 years of age who:
HA to HB 4040 Page 6

1 “(A) Has a developmental or intellectual disability; or
2 “(B) Meets the eligibility criteria to receive services under the Medically Fragile (Hospital)
3 Model Waiver or the Medically Involved Children’s Waiver approved by the Centers for Medicare
4 and Medicaid Services under 42 U.S.C. 1396n(c).
5 “(d) ‘Client’ means an individual who receives attendant care services.
6 “(e) ‘Client child’ means a child who receives attendant care services from the child’s parent.
7 “(f) ‘Developmental disability services’ has the meaning given that term in ORS 427.101.
8 “(g) ‘Direct support professional’ means an individual who is hired, employed, trained, paid and
9 supervised by an agency to provide attendant care services to a client of the agency.
10 “(h) ‘Nonparent caregiver’ means a direct support professional, personal support worker or
11 similar provider who is paid to provide attendant care services to clients who are not the provider’s
12 children.
13 “(i) ‘Parent’ includes a:
14 “(A) Natural or adoptive parent of a child;
15 “(B) Stepparent of a child; and
16 “(C) Legal guardian of a child.
17 “(j)(A) ‘Parent provider’ means a parent who is paid to provide attendant care services to the
18 parent’s minor child.
19 “(B) ‘Parent provider’ does not include a parent who is paid to provide attendant care services
20 to a child who is 18 years of age or older.
21 “(k)(A) ‘Personal support worker’ means an individual who is employed by a client or the client’s
22 representative and paid to provide attendant care services to the client.
23 “(B) ‘Personal support worker’ does not include a direct support professional.
24 “(L) ‘State plan’ means Oregon’s state plan for medical assistance, described in 42 U.S.C. 1396a,
25 approved by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services.
26 “(m) ‘Very high behavioral needs’ means a minor child’s extraordinary needs for support due to
27 the child’s behavioral condition as indicated by a federally approved functional needs assessment
28 adopted by the department that assigns the child to the highest service level.
29 “(n) ‘Very high medical needs’ means a minor child’s extraordinary needs for support due to the
30 child’s medical condition as indicated by a federally approved functional needs assessment adopted
31 by the department that assigns the child to the highest service level.
32 “(2) Subject to rules adopted under subsection (8) of this section, to ORS 427.194 and to avail-
33 able funding, the department shall administer a program to compensate parents to provide attendant
34 care services to the parents’ children who have been assessed by the department to have very high
35 medical or very high behavioral needs.
36 “(3) To be eligible for the program described in this section:
37 “(a) A parent provider must be employed [by an agency and not by the child or the other parent
38 of the child] as a direct support professional or a personal support worker;
39 “(b) The parent provider may not be paid to provide attendant care services to the client child
40 by an agency that is owned by the parent, the client child or any family member or for which the
41 parent or other family member serves in any administrative or leadership capacity, including as a
42 member of a board of directors; and
43 “(c) The agency employing the parent provider to provide attendant care services to the client
44 child:
45 “(A) May not employ a parent provider as an independent contractor;
HA to HB 4040 Page 7

1 “(B) Shall pay parent providers overtime at the same rate and under the same circumstances
2 as direct support professionals who are not parent providers;
3 “(C) Except as authorized by the department by rule, may not pay providers of attendant care
4 services, including parent providers, to provide services to a [minor] child during school hours un-
5 less the [minor] child is temporarily at home recovering from surgery or illness and the temporary
6 absence from school is recommended by the child’s health care provider; and
7 “(D) May not pay providers of attendant care services, including parent providers, to provide
8 services to a [minor] child during school hours due to the determination of a school district or due
9 to the choice of a parent of the [client] child to:
10 “(i) Have the child regularly attend school less than the number of school hours attended by
11 students without disabilities who are in the same grade and the same school district as the [client]
12 child;
13 “(ii) Homeschool the [client] child; or
14 “(iii) Enroll the [client] child in a private school that offers fewer school hours than the school
15 hours offered by the local public school to the majority of students in the same grade as the
16 [client] child.
17 “(4) Subsection (3)(c)(D) of this section does not prohibit a school district or other entity from
18 compensating parents of students with disabilities for providing support for educational activities
19 that would otherwise be the responsibility of the school district.
20 “(5) A parent provider, during the hours that the parent provider is paid to provide one-on-one
21 attendant care services to the client child:
22 “(a) May not be responsible for a vulnerable adult who requires physical care and monitoring;
23 “(b) May not be responsible for the care of [a child] an individual, other than the client child,
