28 for the primary benefit of the client child, including but not limited to:
29 “(A) Grocery shopping for the household;
30 “(B) Housekeeping not required for the disability-related support needs of the client child;
31 “(C) Remote work or operation of a home business; or
32 “(D) Transporting individuals other than the client child to or from activities or appointments.
33 “(6) If required by the Centers for Medicare and Medicaid Services, the department may require
34 a parent provider to assign an alternative legal representative for the client child to make decisions
35 about or manage the development and implementation of the client child’s individual support plan.
36 The assignment:
37 “(a) Must be on a form prescribed by the department; and
38 “(b) Must clearly state that the assignment is limited to decisions regarding the development
39 and implementation of the client child’s individual support plan and does not limit the authority of
40 the parent provider to make decisions for the client child with respect to health care, education or
41 religious training.
42 “(7) A parent provider is subject to the requirements of mandatory reporting of abuse under
43 ORS 124.060 and 419B.010, 24 hours per day, seven days per week.
44 “(8) The department shall adopt rules for the program described in this section using an advi-
45 sory committee appointed under ORS 183.333 that represents the interests of parents, children with
