20 “COMMERCIAL HEALTH INSURANCE
21
22 “SECTION 14. Section 15 of this 2026 Act is added to and made a part of the Insurance
23 Code.
24 “SECTION 15. (1) A group or individual policy of casualty insurance or health insurance,
25 including a health benefit plan as defined in ORS 743B.005, shall provide coverage for med-
26 ically necessary anesthesia services, regardless of the duration, for any procedure covered
27 by the policy.
28 “(2) A policy described in subsection (1) of this section may not deny payment or re-
29 imbursement for anesthesia services solely because the duration of care exceeded a preset
30 time limit.
31 “SECTION 16. Section 15 of this 2026 Act applies to group or individual policies of casu-
32 alty insurance or health insurance, including health benefit plans, that are issued, renewed
33 or extended on or after January 1, 2027.
34 “SECTION 17. Sections 18, 20 and 21 of this 2026 Act are added to and made a part of the
35 Insurance Code.
36 “SECTION 18. As used in ORS 743B.456 and sections 20 and 21 of this 2026 Act:
37 “(1) ‘Dental insurance plan’ means a policy or certificate of insurance or other contract
38 that provides only a dental benefit.
39 “(2) ‘Dental insurer’ means an insurer that offers a policy or certificate of insurance or
40 other contract that provides only a dental benefit.
41 “(3) ‘Dental provider’ means a person licensed, certified or otherwise permitted by laws
42 of this state to administer dental services in the ordinary course of business or practice of
43 a profession.
44 “SECTION 19. ORS 743B.456 is amended to read:
45 “743B.456. (1) As used in this section, [‘dental insurer’ means an insurer that offers a policy or
HA to HB 4040 Page 11

1 certificate of insurance or other contract, that provides only a dental benefit] ‘clean claim’ means a
2 claim that has no defect or error, is understandable and reasonably legible, includes required
3 substantiating documentation and does not require special treatment that delays timely
4 payment on the claim.
5 “(2) A dental insurer may pay a claim for reimbursement made by a dental care provider using
6 a credit card or electronic funds transfer payment method that imposes on the provider a fee or
7 similar charge to process the payment if:
8 “(a) The dental insurer notifies the provider, in advance, of the potential fees or other charges
9 associated with the use of the credit card or electronic funds transfer payment method;
10 “(b) The dental insurer offers the provider an alternative payment method that does not impose
11 fees or similar charges on the provider; and
12 “(c) The provider or a designee of the provider elects to accept a payment of the claim using
13 the credit card or electronic funds transfer payment method.
14 “(3) If a dental insurer contracts with a vendor to process payments of dental providers’ claims,
15 the dental insurer shall require the vendor to comply with the provisions of subsection (2)(a) of this
16 section.
17 “(4) Except as provided in this subsection, when a claim under a dental insurance plan
18 is submitted to a dental insurer by a dental provider on behalf of a beneficiary, the dental
19 insurer shall pay a clean claim or deny the claim not later than 45 days after the date on
20 which the dental insurer receives the claim. If a dental insurer requires additional informa-
21 tion before payment of a claim, not later than 45 days after the date on which the dental
22 insurer receives the claim, the dental insurer shall notify the beneficiary and the dental
23 provider in writing or electronically, and give the beneficiary and the dental provider an ex-
24 planation of the additional information needed to process the claim. The dental insurer shall
25 pay a clean claim or deny the claim not later than 45 days after the date on which the dental
26 insurer receives the additional information.
27 “(5) A contract between a dental insurer and a dental provider may not include a pro-
28 vision governing payment of claims that limits the rights and remedies available to a pro-
29 vider under this section or has the effect of relieving either party of its obligations under
30 this section.
31 “(6) A dental insurer shall establish a method of communicating to dental providers the
32 procedures and information necessary to complete claim forms. The procedures and infor-
33 mation must be reasonably accessible to dental providers.
34 “(7) This section does not create an assignment of payment to a dental provider.
35 “SECTION 20. (1) As used in this section, ‘refund’ means the return, either directly or
36 through an offset to a future claim, of some or all of a payment already received by a dental
37 provider.
38 “(2) Except in the case of fraud or abuse of billing, and except as provided in subsections
39 (3) and (5) of this section, a dental insurer may not:
40 “(a) Request from a dental provider a refund of a payment previously made to satisfy a
41 claim unless the dental insurer:
42 “(A) Requests the refund in writing or electronically on or before the last day of the pe-
43 riod specified by the contract with the dental provider or 18 months after the date the pay-
44 ment was made, whichever is earlier; and
45 “(B) Specifies in the written or electronic request why the dental insurer believes the
HA to HB 4040 Page 12

1 dental provider owes the refund.
2 “(b) Request that a contested refund be paid earlier than six months after the dental
3 provider receives the request.
4 “(3) A dental insurer may not do the following for reasons related to coordination of
5 benefits with another dental insurer or entity responsible for payment of a claim:
6 “(a) Request from a dental provider a refund of a payment previously made to satisfy a
7 claim unless the dental insurer:
8 “(A) Requests the refund in writing or electronically within 45 days after the date the
9 payment was made;
10 “(B) Specifies in the written or electronic request why the dental insurer believes the
11 provider owes the refund; and
12 “(C) Includes in the written or electronic request the name and mailing address of the
13 other dental insurer or entity that has primary responsibility for payment of the claim.
14 “(b) Request that a contested refund be paid earlier than six months after the dental
15 provider receives the request.
16 “(4) If a dental provider fails to contest a refund request in writing or electronically to
17 the dental insurer within 30 days after receiving the request, the request is deemed accepted
18 and the dental provider must pay the refund within 30 days after the request is deemed ac-
19 cepted. If the dental provider has not paid the refund within 30 days after the request is
20 deemed accepted, the dental insurer may recover the amount through an offset to a future
21 claim.
22 “(5) A dental insurer may at any time request from a dental provider a refund of a pay-
23 ment previously made to satisfy a claim if:
24 “(a) A third party, including a government entity, is found responsible for satisfaction
25 of the claim as a consequence of liability imposed by law; and
26 “(b) The dental insurer is unable to recover directly from the third party because the
27 third party has already paid or will pay the provider for the dental services covered by the
28 claim.
29 “(6) If a contract between a dental insurer and a dental provider conflicts with this sec-
30 tion, the provisions of this section prevail. However, nothing in this section prohibits a dental
31 provider from choosing at any time to refund to a dental insurer any payment previously
32 made to satisfy a claim.
33 “(7) This section neither permits nor precludes a dental insurer from recovering from a
34 subscriber, enrollee or beneficiary any amounts paid to a dental provider for benefits to
35 which the subscriber, enrollee or beneficiary was not entitled under the terms and conditions
36 of the dental insurance plan, insurance policy or other benefit agreement.
37 “SECTION 21. A dental provider that bills a dental insurer for covered services provided
38 to an individual who is insured under a dental insurance plan shall be reimbursed by the
39 insurer by a direct payment issued to the dental provider.
40 “SECTION 22. Sections 18, 20 and 21 of this 2026 Act and the amendments to ORS
41 743B.456 by section 19 of this 2026 Act become operative on January 1, 2028.
42 “SECTION 23. (1) As used in this section and section 24 of this 2026 Act, ‘insurance
43 coverage mandate’ means a proposed legislative measure that requires payment for certain
44 services of health care providers or that requires an offering of health insurance coverage
45 by an insurer or a health care service contractor as a component of an individual or group
HA to HB 4040 Page 13

1 health insurance policy.
2 “(2) The Legislative Policy and Research Director shall develop, as a pilot program, an
3 insurance coverage mandate impact statement template. The template must solicit the in-
4 formation sought in section 24 of this 2026 Act and must take into consideration:
5 “(a) Sources of data to be considered in the preparation of an insurance coverage man-
6 date impact statement for proposed legislation; and
7 “(b) Sources of research to be considered in the preparation of an insurance coverage
8 mandate impact statement.
9 “(3) In preparing the template, the director shall consider models used in other states
10 and in academic research for assessing the impacts of proposed insurance coverage mandate
11 legislation and other formal actions undertaken by national, state and local government en-
12 tities and other entities in the United States, including educational institutions.
13 “(4) The director shall confer with the chairs and vice chairs of those committees of the
14 Legislative Assembly having jurisdiction over health care and, based on that conferral,
15 select up to three Senate measures and up to three House measures that were enacted
16 during the 2025 regular session of the Legislative Assembly on which to apply the insurance
17 coverage mandate impact statement template.
18 “(5) Following selection of the measures described in subsection (4) of this section, the
19 director shall apply the template to each of the selected measures and prepare draft insur-
20 ance coverage mandate impact statements for each measure. The director shall present a
21 preliminary report to the committees with jurisdiction over health care on or before Sep-
22 tember 15, 2026, that reports on:
23 “(a) The template methodology and review process;
24 “(b) The director’s experience in preparing draft impact statements; and
25 “(c) The specific findings of the draft impact statements prepared for the test measures.
26 “(6) Based on feedback provided by the committees with jurisdiction over health care, the
27 director may modify the template and prepare final insurance coverage mandate impact
28 statements on the test measures. The director shall present the final impact statements and
29 the final process report summarizing the methodology used to prepare and review impact
30 statements to the policy committees that had heard the test measures during the 2025 reg-
31 ular session of the Legislative Assembly. The director shall present the statements and final
32 report to the committees on or before December 15, 2026.
33 “(7) Following the presentations described in subsection (5) of this section and following
34 or contemporaneously with the presentations described in subsection (6) of this section and
35 taking into account provided feedback, the director shall propose to the committees with
36 jurisdiction over health care a policy that describes the objectives, content and form of an
37 insurance coverage mandate impact statement and the procedures to be followed in the
38 preparation of those statements. After conducting due deliberations in which the committees
39 may make modifications to the policy, the committees shall adopt a policy on the preparation
40 of insurance coverage mandate impact statements. The policy shall include guidance on when
41 an insurance coverage mandate impact statement must be posted online on the Legislative
42 Assembly website, relative to the location in the legislative process of the associated legis-
43 lative measure.
44 “SECTION 24. An insurance coverage mandate impact statement required to be devel-
45 oped under section 23 of this 2026 Act shall include but need not be limited to the following:
HA to HB 4040 Page 14

1 “(1) The evidence that exists to document the medical need for the treatment or service
2 covered under the proposed legislative measure;
3 “(2) The extent of the coverage under the proposed measure;
4 “(3) Whether the proposed measure ensures more or less equitable access to treatment
5 or services by residents of this state;
6 “(4) Whether denying the coverage under the proposed measure would disproportionately
7 impact individuals described in ORS 746.021 and, if so, a description of the impact;
8 “(5) Whether the coverage under the proposed measure is an essential health benefit as
9 defined in ORS 731.097;
10 “(6) A listing of other state or federal laws that relate to the proposed measure, including
11 whether other states are defraying the cost of similar coverage in accordance with 42
12 U.S.C. 18031(d)(3), as amended and in effect on the effective date of this 2026 Act;
13 “(7) The extent to which the coverage in the proposed measure is already provided by the
14 Public Employees’ Benefit Board, the Oregon Educators Benefit Board or individual, small
15 employer group and large employer group health insurance plans;
16 “(8) The extent to which the coverage in the proposed measure is provided in the state
17 medical assistance program as prescribed by the Oregon Health Authority under ORS 414.065
18 or in Medicare Parts A through D; and
19 “(9) The extent to which a lack of the coverage in the proposed measure results in fi-
20 nancial hardship to residents of this state.
21 “SECTION 25. No later than September 15, 2027, the Legislative Policy and Research Di-
22 rector shall report to the Legislative Assembly in the manner provided under ORS 192.245
23 on recommendations for changes to improve upon the review of proposed insurance coverage
24 mandates during regular or special sessions of the Legislative Assembly. The recommen-
25 dations may include legislative proposals or explanations of the need for additional resources.
