34 “SECTION 33. ORS 743A.145 is amended to read:
35 “743A.145. (1) As used in this section:
36 “(a) ‘Device’ means:
37 “(A) An orthotic device.
38 “(B) A prosthetic device.
39 “(b) ‘Orthotic device’ means a rigid or semirigid device supporting a weak or deformed leg, foot,
40 arm, hand, back or neck, or restricting or eliminating motion in a diseased or injured leg, foot, arm,
41 hand, back or neck.
42 “(c) ‘Prosthetic device’ means an artificial limb device or appliance designed to replace in whole
43 or in part an arm or a leg.
44 “(2) All individual and group health insurance policies providing coverage for the expenses of
45 hospital, medical or surgical services or supplies shall provide coverage for devices. The coverage
HA to HB 4040 Page 21

1 required by this subsection includes:
2 “(a) Devices that are determined to be medically necessary to restore or maintain the ability to
3 complete activities of daily living or essential job-related activities [and that are not solely for com-
4 fort or convenience].
5 “(b) All services and supplies medically necessary for the effective use of a device, including
6 design formulation, fabrication, material and component selection, measurements, fittings, static and
7 dynamic alignments and patient instruction in the use of the device.
8 “(c) Replacement of a device or any part of a device, if the replacement is determined to be
9 medically necessary, based on:
10 “(A) A change in the physiological condition of the insured;
11 “(B) An irreparable change in the condition of the device or part of the device; or
12 “(C) The device, or a part of the device, requiring repair and the cost of the repair would be
13 more than 60 percent of the cost of the replacement device or replacement part of the device.
14 “(d) Repair of a device or any part of a device, if the repair is determined to be medically nec-
15 essary, based on:
16 “(A) A change in the physiological condition of the insured; or
17 “(B) A change in the condition of the device or part of the device.
18 “(e) Devices that are determined to be medically necessary and the most appropriate model that
19 meets the medical needs of the insured for purposes of performing physical activities, including but
20 not limited to running, biking, swimming and strength training, and that maximizes the insured’s
21 whole-body health, including lower and upper limb function.
22 “(3) The Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services shall adopt and annu-
23 ally update rules listing the devices covered under this section. The list shall be no more restrictive
24 than the list of devices and supplies in the Medicare fee schedule for Durable Medical Equipment,
25 Prosthetics, Orthotics and Supplies, but only to the extent consistent with this section.
26 “(4) The coverage required by subsection (2) of this section may be made subject to, and no more
27 restrictive than, the provisions of a health insurance policy that apply to other benefits under the
28 policy.
29 “(5) If the coverage under subsection (2) of this section is provided through a managed care
30 organization, the insured shall have access to medically necessary clinical care and to devices and
31 technology from not fewer than two distinct Oregon prosthetic and orthotic providers in the man-
32 aged care organization’s provider network.
33 “(6) An individual or group health plan may not deny coverage for a prosthetic or orthotic
34 benefit for an insured with limb loss, impairment or absence to restore or maintain the ability to
35 perform a physical activity if a benefit would be covered for medical or surgical intervention for a
36 person without limb loss, impairment or absence to restore or maintain the ability to perform the
37 same physical activity.
38 “(7) For coverage described in subsection (2)(c) of this section, an insurer may require confir-
39 mation from the prescribing health care provider that the coverage is medically necessary if the
40 device, or any part of the device, requires replacement and is less than three years old.
41 “(8) This section is exempt from ORS 743A.001.
42 “(9) The coverage requirements described in subsections (2)(e), (6) and (7) of this section do not
43 apply to a health benefit plan offered by the Public Employees’ Benefit Board or the Oregon Edu-
44 cators Benefit Board, unless the plans offered by the Public Employees’ Benefit Board or the Oregon
45 Educators Benefit Board elect to provide the coverage and provide notice to the Department of
