5 “SECTION 34. ORS 744.702 is amended to read:
6 “744.702. (1) Subject to ORS 744.704, a person shall not transact business or purport or offer to
7 transact business as a third party administrator in this state unless the person holds a third party
8 administrator license issued by the Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services.
9 “(2) For purposes of ORS 744.700 to 744.740, a person transacts or purports or offers to transact
10 business as a third party administrator if the person:
11 “(a) Directly or indirectly solicits or effects coverage of, underwrites, collects charges or pre-
12 miums from, or adjusts or settles claims on, residents of this state or residents of another state from
13 offices in this state, in connection with life insurance or health insurance coverage; or
14 “(b) Acts as a pharmacy services administrative organization, as defined in ORS 735.538, or as
15 an organization that advises or represents pharmacies that are members of the organization, or that
16 enters into contracts on behalf of members, in matters that are related to procuring or supplying
17 prescription drugs.
18 “(3) A pharmacy services administrative organization, as defined in ORS 735.538, is exempt from
19 the requirement to obtain a license under [ORS 735.538] subsection (2) of this section, if the
20 pharmacy services administrative organization is not owned by a pharmacy benefit manager and
21 generates revenue only from monthly service fees that a pharmacy pays for services that are not
22 connected to drug pricing or volume.
23 “(4) Nothing in ORS 744.700 to 744.740 exempts a third party administrator from any other ap-
24 plicable licensing requirement when the third party administrator performs the functions of an in-
25 surance producer, adjuster or insurance consultant.
26 “SECTION 35. ORS 646A.694 is amended to read:
27 “646A.694. (1) The Department of Consumer and Business Services shall provide to the Pre-
28 scription Drug Affordability Board each calendar year a list of prescription drugs included in re-
29 ports submitted to the department under ORS 646A.689 (2) and (6), a list of drugs included in reports
30 submitted to the department under ORS 646A.683 and 743.025 and a list of insulin drugs marketed
31 in this state during the previous calendar year. Each calendar year, the board shall identify up to
32 nine drugs and may identify at least one insulin product from the lists provided under this sub-
33 section that the board determines may create affordability challenges for health care systems or
34 high out-of-pocket costs for patients in this state based on criteria adopted by the board by rule,
35 including but not limited to:
36 “(a) Whether the prescription drug has led to health inequities in communities of color;
37 “(b) The number of residents in this state prescribed the prescription drug;
38 “(c) The price for the prescription drug sold in this state;
39 “(d) The estimated average monetary price concession, discount or rebate the manufacturer
40 provides to health insurance plans in this state or is expected to provide to health insurance plans
41 in this state, expressed as a percentage of the price for the prescription drug under review;
42 “(e) The estimated total amount of the price concession, discount or rebate the manufacturer
43 provides to each pharmacy benefit manager licensed in this state for the prescription drug under
44 review, expressed as a percentage of the prices;
45 “(f) The estimated price for therapeutic alternatives to the drug that are sold in this state;
HA to HB 4040 Page 23

1 “(g) The estimated average price concession, discount or rebate the manufacturer provides or
2 is expected to provide to health insurance plans and pharmacy benefit managers in this state for
3 therapeutic alternatives;
4 “(h) The estimated costs to health insurance plans based on patient use of the drug consistent
5 with the labeling approved by the United States Food and Drug Administration and recognized
6 standard medical practice;
7 “(i) The impact on patient access to the drug considering standard prescription drug benefit
8 designs in health insurance plans offered in this state;
9 “(j) The relative financial impacts to health, medical or social services costs as can be quantified
10 and compared to the costs of existing therapeutic alternatives;
11 “(k) The estimated average patient copayment or other cost-sharing for the prescription drug in
12 this state;
13 “(L) Any information a manufacturer chooses to provide; and
14 “(m) Any other factors as determined by the board in rules adopted by the board.
15 “(2) A drug that is designated by the Secretary of the United States Food and Drug Adminis-
16 tration, under 21 U.S.C. 360bb, as a drug for a rare disease or condition is not subject to review
17 under subsection (1) of this section.
18 “(3) The board shall accept testimony from patients and caregivers affected by a condition or
19 disease that is treated by a prescription drug under review by the board and from individuals with
20 scientific or medical training with respect to the disease or condition.
21 “(4)(a) If the board considers the cost-effectiveness of a prescription drug in criteria adopted by
22 the board under subsection (1) of this section, the board may not use quality-adjusted life-years, or
23 similar formulas that take into account a patient’s age or severity of illness or disability, to identify
24 subpopulations for which a prescription drug would be less cost-effective. For any prescription drug
25 that extends life, the board’s analysis of cost-effectiveness must weigh the value of the quality of life
26 equally for all patients, regardless of the patients’ age or severity of illness or disability.
27 “(b) As used in this subsection:
28 “(A) ‘Health utility’ means a measure of the degree to which having a particular form of disease
29 or disability or having particular functional limitations negatively impacts the quality of life as
30 compared to a state of perfect health, expressed as a number between zero and one.
31 “(B) ‘Quality-adjusted life-year’ is the product of a health utility multiplied by the extra months
32 or years of life that a patient might gain as a result of a treatment.
33 “(5) To the extent practicable, the board shall access pricing information for prescription drugs
34 by:
35 “(a) Accessing pricing information collected by the department under ORS 646A.689 and 743.025;
36 “(b) Accessing data reported to the Oregon Health Authority under ORS 442.373;
37 “(c) Entering into a memorandum of understanding with another state to which manufacturers
38 already report pricing information; and
39 “(d) Accessing other publicly available pricing information.
40 “(6) The information used to conduct an affordability review may include any document and re-
41 search related to the introductory price or price increase of a prescription drug, including life cycle
42 management, net average price in this state, market competition and context, projected revenue and
43 the estimated value or cost-effectiveness of the prescription drug.
