9 “(4) ‘Carrier-insured employer’ means an employer who provides workers’ compensation cover-
10 age with the State Accident Insurance Fund Corporation or an insurer authorized under ORS
11 chapter 731 to transact workers’ compensation insurance in this state.
12 “(5) ‘Child’ means a child of an injured worker, including:
13 “(a) A posthumous child;
14 “(b) A child legally adopted before the injury;
15 “(c) A child toward whom the worker stands in loco parentis;
16 “(d) A child born out of wedlock;
17 “(e) A stepchild, if the stepchild was, at the time of the injury, a member of the worker’s family
18 and substantially dependent upon the worker for support; and
19 “(f) A child of any age who was incapacitated at the time of the accident and thereafter remains
20 incapacitated and substantially dependent on the worker for support.
21 “(6) ‘Claim’ means a written request for compensation from a subject worker or someone on the
22 worker’s behalf, or any compensable injury of which a subject employer has notice or knowledge.
23 “(7)(a) A ‘compensable injury’ is an accidental injury, or accidental injury to prosthetic appli-
24 ances, arising out of and in the course of employment requiring medical services or resulting in
25 disability or death. An injury is accidental if the result is an accident, whether or not due to acci-
26 dental means, if it is established by medical evidence supported by objective findings, subject to the
27 following limitations:
28 “(A) An injury or disease is not compensable as a consequence of a compensable injury unless
29 the compensable injury is the major contributing cause of the consequential condition.
30 “(B) If an otherwise compensable injury combines at any time with a preexisting condition to
31 cause or prolong disability or a need for treatment, the combined condition is compensable only if,
32 so long as and to the extent that the otherwise compensable injury is the major contributing cause
33 of the disability of the combined condition or the major contributing cause of the need for treatment
34 of the combined condition.
35 “(b) ‘Compensable injury’ does not include:
36 “(A) Injury to any active participant in assaults or combats that are not connected to the job
37 assignment and that amount to a deviation from customary duties;
38 “(B) Injury incurred while engaging in or performing, or as the result of engaging in or per-
39 forming, any recreational or social activities primarily for the worker’s personal pleasure; or
40 “(C) Injury the major contributing cause of which is demonstrated to be by a preponderance of
41 the evidence the injured worker’s consumption of alcoholic beverages or cannabis or the unlawful
42 consumption of any controlled substance, unless the employer permitted, encouraged or had actual
43 knowledge of such consumption.
44 “(c) A ‘disabling compensable injury’ is an injury that entitles the worker to compensation for
45 disability or death. An injury is not disabling if no temporary benefits are due and payable, unless
