28 “656.214. (1) As used in this section:
29 “(a) ‘Impairment’ means the loss of use or function of a body part or system due to the
30 compensable industrial injury or occupational disease determined in accordance with the standards
31 provided under ORS 656.726, expressed as a percentage of the whole person.
32 “(b) ‘Loss’ includes permanent and complete or partial loss of use.
33 “(c) ‘Permanent partial disability’ means:
34 “(A) Permanent impairment resulting from the compensable industrial injury or occupational
35 disease; or
36 “(B) Permanent impairment and work disability resulting from the compensable industrial injury
37 or occupational disease.
38 “(d) ‘Regular work’ means the job the worker held at injury.
39 “(e) ‘Work disability’ means impairment modified by age, education and adaptability to perform
40 a given job.
41 “(2) When permanent partial disability results from a compensable injury or occupational dis-
42 ease, benefits shall be awarded as follows:
43 “(a) If the worker has been released to regular work by the attending physician [or nurse prac-
44 titioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] or has returned to
45 regular work [at the job held at the time of injury], the award shall be for impairment only. Impair-
HA to HB 4040 Page 38

1 ment shall be determined in accordance with the standards provided by the Director of the Depart-
2 ment of Consumer and Business Services pursuant to ORS 656.726 (4). Impairment benefits are
3 determined by multiplying the impairment value times 100 times the average weekly wage as defined
4 by ORS 656.005.
5 “(b) If the worker has not been released to regular work by the attending physician [or nurse
6 practitioner authorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] or has not re-
7 turned to regular work [at the job held at the time of injury], the award shall be for impairment and
8 work disability. Work disability shall be determined in accordance with the standards provided by
9 the director pursuant to ORS 656.726 (4). Impairment shall be determined as provided in paragraph
10 (a) of this subsection. Work disability benefits shall be determined by multiplying the impairment
11 value, as modified by the factors of age, education and adaptability to perform a given job, times
12 150 times the worker’s weekly wage for the job at injury as calculated under ORS 656.210 (2). The
13 factor for the worker’s weekly wage used for the determination of the work disability may be no
14 more than 133 percent or no less than 50 percent of the average weekly wage as defined in ORS
15 656.005.
16 “(3) Impairment benefits awarded under subsection (2)(a) of this section shall be expressed as a
17 percentage of the whole person. Impairment benefits for the following body parts may not exceed:
18 “(a) For the loss of one arm at or above the elbow joint, 60 percent.
19 “(b) For the loss of one forearm at or above the wrist joint, or the loss of one hand, 47 percent.
20 “(c) For the loss of one leg, at or above the knee joint, 47 percent.
21 “(d) For the loss of one foot, 42 percent.
22 “(e) For the loss of a great toe, six percent; for loss of any other toe, one percent.
23 “(f) For partial or complete loss of hearing in one ear, that proportion of 19 percent which the
24 loss bears to normal monaural hearing.
25 “(g) For partial or complete loss of hearing in both ears, that proportion of 60 percent which
26 the combined binaural hearing loss bears to normal combined binaural hearing. For the purpose of
27 this paragraph, combined binaural hearing loss shall be calculated by taking seven times the hearing
28 loss in the less damaged ear plus the hearing loss in the more damaged ear and dividing that amount
29 by eight. In the case of individuals with compensable hearing loss involving both ears, either the
30 method of calculation for monaural hearing loss or that for combined binaural hearing loss shall be
31 used, depending upon which allows the greater award of impairment.
32 “(h) For partial or complete loss of vision of one eye, that proportion of 31 percent which the
33 loss of monocular vision bears to normal monocular vision. For the purposes of this paragraph, the
34 term ‘normal monocular vision’ shall be considered as Snellen 20/20 for distance and Snellen 14/14
35 for near vision with full sensory field.
36 “(i) For partial loss of vision in both eyes, that proportion of 94 percent which the combined
37 binocular visual loss bears to normal combined binocular vision. In all cases of partial loss of sight,
38 the percentage of said loss shall be measured with maximum correction. For the purpose of this
39 paragraph, combined binocular visual loss shall be calculated by taking three times the visual loss
40 in the less damaged eye plus the visual loss in the more damaged eye and dividing that amount by
41 four. In the case of individuals with compensable visual loss involving both eyes, either the method
42 of calculation for monocular visual loss or that for combined binocular visual loss shall be used,
43 depending upon which allows the greater award of impairment.
44 “(j) For the loss of a thumb, 15 percent.
45 “(k) For the loss of a first finger, eight percent; of a second finger, seven percent; of a third
