3 and issue a denial at any time when the denial is for fraud, misrepresentation or other illegal ac-
4 tivity by the worker. If the worker requests a hearing on any revocation of acceptance and denial
5 alleging fraud, misrepresentation or other illegal activity, the insurer or self-insured employer has
6 the burden of proving, by a preponderance of the evidence, such fraud, misrepresentation or other
7 illegal activity. Upon such proof, the worker then has the burden of proving, by a preponderance
8 of the evidence, the compensability of the claim. If the insurer or self-insured employer accepts a
9 claim in good faith, in a case not involving fraud, misrepresentation or other illegal activity by the
10 worker, and later obtains evidence that the claim is not compensable or evidence that the insurer
11 or self-insured employer is not responsible for the claim, the insurer or self-insured employer may
12 revoke the claim acceptance and issue a formal notice of claim denial, if such revocation of ac-
13 ceptance and denial is issued no later than two years after the date of the initial acceptance. If the
14 worker requests a hearing on such revocation of acceptance and denial, the insurer or self-insured
15 employer must prove, by a preponderance of the evidence, that the claim is not compensable or that
16 the insurer or self-insured employer is not responsible for the claim. Notwithstanding any other
17 provision of this chapter, if a denial of a previously accepted claim is set aside by an Administrative
