20 “(c) Eligibility may be redetermined by the insurer or self-insured employer upon receipt of new
21 information that would change the eligibility determination.
22 “(2) Contact under subsection (1) of this section shall include informing the worker about re-
23 employment rights, the responsibility of the worker to request reemployment, and wage subsidy and
24 job site modification assistance and the provisions of the preferred worker program pursuant to
25 rules adopted by the Director of the Department of Consumer and Business Services.
26 “(3) Within five days after notification that the attending physician [or nurse practitioner au-
27 thorized to provide compensable medical services under ORS 656.245] has released a worker to return
28 to work, the insurer or self-insured employer shall inform the worker about the opportunity to seek
29 reemployment or reinstatement under ORS 659A.043 and 659A.046. The insurer shall inform the
30 employer of the worker’s reemployment rights, wage subsidy and the job site modification assistance
31 and the provisions of the preferred worker program.
32 “(4) As soon as possible, and not more than 30 days after the contact required by subsection (1)
33 of this section, the insurer or self-insured employer shall cause an individual certified by the direc-
34 tor to provide vocational assistance to determine whether the worker is eligible for vocational as-
35 sistance. The insurer or self-insured employer shall notify the worker of the decision regarding the
36 worker’s eligibility for vocational assistance. If the insurer or self-insured employer decides that the
37 worker is not eligible, the worker may apply to the director for review of the decision as provided
38 in subsection (16) of this section. A worker determined ineligible upon evaluation under subsection
39 (1)(b)(B) of this section, or because the worker’s eligibility has fully and finally expired under stan-
40 dards prescribed by the director, may not be found eligible thereafter unless that eligibility deter-
41 mination is rejected by the director under subsection (16) of this section or the worker’s condition
42 worsens so as to constitute an aggravation claim under ORS 656.273. A worker is not entitled to
43 vocational assistance benefits when possible eligibility for such benefits arises from a worsening of
44 the worker’s condition that occurs after the expiration of the worker’s aggravation rights under ORS
45 656.273.
HA to HB 4040 Page 60

1 “(5) The objectives of vocational assistance are to return the worker to employment which is
2 as close as possible to the worker’s regular employment at a wage as close as possible to the weekly
3 wage currently being paid for employment which was the worker’s regular employment even though
4 the wage available following employment may be less than the wage prescribed by subsection (6)
5 of this section. As used in this subsection and subsection (6) of this section, ‘regular employment’
6 means the employment the worker held at the time of the injury or the claim for aggravation under
7 ORS 656.273, whichever gave rise to the potential eligibility for vocational assistance; or, for a
8 worker not employed at the time of the aggravation, the employment the worker held on the last
9 day of work prior to the aggravation.
10 “(6)(a) A worker is eligible for vocational assistance if the worker will not be able to return to
11 the previous employment or to any other available and suitable employment with the employer at
12 the time of injury or aggravation, and the worker has a substantial handicap to employment.
13 “(b) As used in this subsection:
14 “(A) A ‘substantial handicap to employment’ exists when the worker, because of the injury or
15 aggravation, lacks the necessary physical capacities, knowledge, skills and abilities to be employed
16 in suitable employment.
17 “(B) ‘Suitable employment’ means:
18 “(i) Employment of the kind for which the worker has the necessary physical capacity, knowl-
19 edge, skills and abilities;
20 “(ii) Employment that is located where the worker customarily worked or is within reasonable
21 commuting distance of the worker’s residence; and
22 “(iii) Employment that produces a weekly wage within 20 percent of that currently being paid
23 for employment that was the worker’s regular employment as defined in subsection (5) of this sec-
24 tion. The director shall adopt rules providing methods of calculating the weekly wage currently be-
25 ing paid for the worker’s regular employment for use in determining eligibility and for providing
26 assistance to eligible workers. If the worker’s regular employment was seasonal or temporary, the
27 worker’s wage shall be averaged based on a combination of the worker’s earned income and any
28 unemployment insurance payments. Only earned income evidenced by verifiable documentation such
29 as federal or state tax returns shall be used in the calculation. Earned income does not include
30 fringe benefits or reimbursement of the worker’s employment expenses.
31 “(7) Vocational evaluation, help in directly obtaining employment and training shall be available
32 under conditions prescribed by the director. The director may establish other conditions for pro-
33 viding vocational assistance, including those relating to the worker’s availability for assistance,
34 participation in previous assistance programs connected with the same claim and the nature and
35 extent of assistance that may be provided. Such conditions shall give preference to direct employ-
36 ment assistance over training.
37 “(8) An insurer or self-insured employer may utilize its own staff or may engage any other in-
38 dividual certified by the director to perform the vocational evaluation required by subsection (4) of
39 this section.
40 “(9) The director shall adopt rules providing:
41 “(a) Standards for and methods of certifying individuals qualified by education, training and ex-
42 perience to provide vocational assistance to injured workers;
43 “(b) Standards for registration of vocational assistance providers;
44 “(c) Conditions and procedures under which the certification of an individual to provide voca-
45 tional assistance services or the registration of a vocational assistance provider may be suspended
HA to HB 4040 Page 61

1 or revoked for failure to maintain compliance with the certification or registration standards;
2 “(d) Standards for the nature and extent of services a worker may receive, for plans for return
3 to work and for determining when the worker has returned to work; and
4 “(e) Procedures, schedules and conditions relating to the payment for services performed by a
5 vocational assistance provider, that are based on payment for specific services performed and not
6 fees for services performed on an hourly basis. Fee schedules shall reflect a reasonable rate for
7 direct worker purchases and for all vocational assistance providers and shall be the same within
8 suitable geographic areas.
9 “(10) Insurers and self-insured employers shall maintain records and make reports to the direc-
10 tor of vocational assistance actions at times and in the manner as the director may prescribe. The
11 requirements prescribed shall be for the purpose of assisting the Department of Consumer and
12 Business Services in monitoring compliance with this section to insure that workers receive timely
13 and appropriate vocational assistance. The director shall minimize to the greatest extent possible
14 the number, extent and kinds of reports required. The director shall compile a list of organizations
15 or agencies registered to provide vocational assistance. A current list shall be distributed by the
16 director to all insurers and self-insured employers. The insurer shall send the list to each worker
17 with the notice of eligibility.
18 “(11) When a worker is eligible to receive vocational assistance, the worker and the insurer or
19 self-insured employer shall attempt to agree on the choice of a vocational assistance provider. If the
20 worker agrees, the insurer or self-insured employer may utilize its own staff to provide vocational
21 assistance. If they are unable to agree on a vocational assistance provider, the insurer or self-
22 insured employer shall notify the director and the director shall select a provider. Any change in
23 the choice of vocational assistance provider is subject to the approval of the director.
24 “(12) Notwithstanding ORS 656.268, a worker actively engaged in training may receive tempo-
25 rary disability compensation for a maximum of 16 months. The insurer or self-insured employer may
26 voluntarily extend the payment of temporary disability compensation to a maximum of 21 months.
27 The director may order the payment of temporary disability compensation for up to 21 months upon
28 good cause shown by the injured worker. The costs related to vocational assistance training pro-
29 grams may be paid for periods longer than 21 months, but in no event may temporary disability
30 benefits be paid for a period longer than 21 months.
31 “(13) As used in this section, ‘vocational assistance provider’ means a public or private organ-
32 ization or agency that provides vocational assistance to injured workers.
33 “(14)(a) Determination of eligibility for vocational assistance does not entitle all workers to the
34 same type or extent of assistance.
35 “(b) Training shall not be provided to an eligible worker solely because the worker cannot ob-
36 tain employment, otherwise suitable, that will produce the wage prescribed in subsection (6) of this
37 section unless such training will enable the worker to find employment which will produce a wage
38 significantly closer to that prescribed in subsection (6) of this section.
39 “(c) Nothing in this section shall be interpreted to expand the availability of training under this
40 section.
