4 “(16)(a) The Legislative Assembly finds that vocational rehabilitation of injured workers re-
5 quires a high degree of cooperation between all of the participants in the vocational assistance
6 process. Based on this finding, the Legislative Assembly concludes that disputes regarding eligibility
7 for and extent of vocational assistance services should be resolved through nonadversarial proce-
8 dures to the greatest extent possible consistent with constitutional principles. The director shall
9 adopt by rule a procedure for resolving vocational assistance disputes in the manner provided in this
10 subsection.
11 “(b) If a worker is dissatisfied with an action of the insurer or self-insured employer regarding
12 vocational assistance, the worker must apply to the director for administrative review of the matter.
13 Application for review must be made not later than the 60th day after the date the worker was
14 notified of the action. The director shall complete the review within a reasonable time.
15 “(c) If the worker’s dissatisfaction is resolved by agreement of the parties, the agreement shall
16 be reduced to writing, and the director and the parties shall review the agreement and either ap-
17 prove or disapprove it. The agreement is subject to reconsideration by the director under limitations
18 prescribed by the director, but is not subject to review by any other forum.
19 “(d) If the worker’s dissatisfaction is not resolved by agreement of the parties, the director shall
20 resolve the matter in a written order based on a record sufficient to permit review. The order is
21 subject to review under ORS 656.704. The request for a hearing must be filed within 60 days of the
22 date the order was issued. At the hearing, the order of the director shall be modified only if it:
23 “(A) Violates a statute or rule;
24 “(B) Exceeds the statutory authority of the agency;
25 “(C) Was made upon unlawful procedure; or
26 “(D) Was characterized by abuse of discretion or clearly unwarranted exercise of discretion.
